{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"433"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/433"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.01,0.15,0.67,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41710"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41710"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman becomes confused and disoriented five days after an emergency bowel resection for perforated diverticulitis. She has no relevant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears unwell. Her pulse is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 90% on room air and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. On respiratory examination there is dullness to percussion and reduced breath sounds at the right lung base.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be the first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous gentamicin, amoxicillin and metronidazole","A one litre bolus of intravenous saline","Chest X-ray","Oxygen via face mask at 15L/min","Blood collection for culture, biochemistry and haematology"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe approach to any deteriorating patient should begin with \u2018DRSABC\u2019, also known as the primary survey. This provides a systematic, prioritised approach to stabilise the patient before exploring further differentials and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs such, following evaluation of danger, response, sending for help and assessing airway patency, it is prudent to apply \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen (ideally 15L via non-rebreather mask) \u003C/strong\u003Eto all deteriorating patients prior to further assessment - particularly in those exhibiting signs of hypoxia. \u003Cstrong\u003EEach of the alternative answers\u003C/strong\u003E are reasonable and would be done in these circumstances, however the priority must remain in order of the primary survey (i.e. oxygenation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s confusion could be due to many causes. Given her hypoxia and fever it is most likely secondary to pneumonia, but a wide list of differentials should be considered. Memory aids such as \u2018Wind, Wound, Walking, and Water\u201d can be utilised in remembering common post-operative complications. Whilst the underlying cause must be identified and treated, the priority must be to deal with her hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A primary survey should be prioritised in the assessment of a deteriorating patient","Pneumonia is a common post-operative complication leading to hypoxia and fever"],"references":["Maity A, Saha D, Swaika S, Maulik SG, Choudhury B, Sutradhar M. Detection of hypoxia in the early postoperative period. Anesth Essays Res. 2012;6(1):34-37. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4173444/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"433"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-22T10:12:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-22T10:12:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"433"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41710"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings